I was given a map of a city I had never seen. I was told that I would have no trouble in finding my way about, said a friendly person, but a map will certainly help. So I will get one for you. And he set out at once on his own journey. I walked on, and was met by a woman. Here, she said, is an umbrella, for I see from the weather-vane that it is likely to rain. The weather-vane was on the Town Hall. It showed a golden cockerel with his tail blown out in the north wind. I looked about me. It was a beautiful old city, with mellow brick houses and a great many trees, and it stood upon a hill. Down below was a river and a ring of meadows. What do you think of our city? asked the Lord Mayor, stepping from his front door in a red gown trimmed with fur. We are proud of our city, and we mean to take good care of it. Have you noticed our fine new traffic-signs? I could not say that I had. They had not been put up. But I saw that great care was being taken in other matters. The litter-baskets, for instance, were beautiful. They were of a pleasant shape, coloured a modest grey, and lettered in a graceful script which I was told was the work of a student from the Art School. And on them was the simple request PLEASE KEEP YOUR CITY TIDY. I must own that I could see no litter. It may be that the litter-baskets were so beautiful that people came from far and near to put their litter in them. There were a great many people walking about, and they were all so considerate that they made way for me on the pavement. I was a stranger there, but they could not have been kinder. On the day I left, I went to say good-bye to the Lord Mayor. Thank you for all you have done for me, I said. We have done nothing, he replied. Come and see us again when our traffic-signs are up. So I took a last look at the golden cockerel, and went upon my way.
